Starting by construction target variable and checking classes balance count:¶

Target variable is a binarization of percentage change in the value of BTC so let's:¶

  • shift b_value 15 days so we can classify next change in value
  • construct a binary target target
  • drop nan row in the begginnig and also drop b_value
  • check classes balance
In [4]:
df['target'] = df['b_value'].shift(-15) - df['b_value'] > 0
df = df[df.index.year == 2015]

df.drop(columns='b_value', inplace=True)
df.dropna(inplace=True)

print('Classes balance:')
print(df['target'].value_counts() / len(df['target']))

weight_instance = 1 / (df['target'].value_counts().values / len(df['target']))

Feature Normalization: for variables which are not binary¶

In [6]:
from utilities import non_bool_cols

to_scale = non_bool_cols(X_train)

# get min and max from train
X_min, X_max = X_train[to_scale].min(axis=0), X_train[to_scale].max(axis=0)

X_train_scaled = X_train.copy()
X_test_scaled = X_test.copy()

# print(X_train.head())
X_train_scaled[to_scale] = (X_train_scaled[to_scale] - X_min) / (X_max - X_min)

# scale test data with training value to avoid data leakage
X_test_scaled[to_scale] = (X_test_scaled[to_scale] - X_min) / (X_max - X_min)

Decision Trees¶

In [14]:
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score

clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=3).fit(X_train, y_train)
        
print('Accuracy of Decision Tree classifier on training set: {:.2f}'
     .format(f1_score(y_train, clf.predict(X_train), average='macro')))
print('Accuracy of Decision Tree classifier on test set: {:.2f}'
     .format(f1_score(y_test, clf.predict(X_test), average='macro')))

Accuracy of Decision Tree classifier on training set: 0.85
